Reasoning: We inspected the workbook and found it contains a sheet named "Blad1" with no data in column B (rows 8‑20 are empty). The instruction requires that cell B12 compute the average of B11:B12, cell B13 compute the average of B11:B13, and that the result be rounded to three decimal places. To satisfy this (and any future rows), we will write a formula in each cell from row 12 down to the current maximum row (16) using the pattern:

```
=ROUND(AVERAGE($B$11:B{row}),3)
```

This formula fixes the start of the range at B11 (`$B$11`) and lets the end of the range be the current row, so it automatically expands when new data is added. We will write these formulas with openpyxl, save the modified workbook to the output directory, and then reload it with `data_only=True` to verify that the formulas are present.
Code:
```repl
import os
from openpyxl import load_workbook

# Paths
input_path = "/sandbox/input/input_spreadsheet/1_43213_init.xlsx"
output_dir = "/sandbox/output/output_spreadsheet"
os.makedirs(output_dir, exist_ok=True)
output_path = os.path.join(output_dir, "1_43213_init.xlsx")

# Load workbook (read/write)
wb = load_workbook(input_path)  # keep formulas
ws = wb.active  # assume first sheet is the target

# Determine the last row to fill (current max row)
last_row = ws.max_row

# Write average formulas for rows 12 .. last_row
for row in range(12, last_row + 1):
    # Formula: round(average($B$11:B{row}), 3)
    formula = f"=ROUND(AVERAGE($B$11:B{row}),3)"
    ws.cell(row=row, column=2).value = formula  # column 2 = B

# Save the modified workbook
wb.save(output_path)
print(f"Saved modified workbook to {output_path}")

# Verify by reloading with data_only=True (formulas will appear as text)
wb_check = load_workbook(output_path, data_only=False)
ws_check = wb_check.active
for row in range(12, last_row + 1):
    cell = ws_check.cell(row=row, column=2)
    print(f"B{row} formula: {cell.value}")
```
